### Notable Sportspeople

Adding a touch of international flair to Shikoku's sporting achievements, two-time darts Women's World Champion [Mikuru Suzuki](/Mikuru_Suzuki) hails from [Takamatsu](/Takamatsu) in [Kagawa Prefecture](/Kagawa_Prefecture) on Shikoku. Her success on the global stage demonstrates that talent can emerge from any corner, even if it's not always in the most traditionally revered national sports.

## Transportation

### Roads

[Kōchi Castle](/K%C5%8Dchi_Castle)
Anraku-ji in Kamiita, [Tokushima](/Tokushima,_Tokushima)

Shikoku’s relative isolation was significantly mitigated by the ambitious [Honshū–Shikoku Bridge Project](/Honsh%C5%AB%E2%80%93Shikoku_Bridge_Project), a monumental feat of engineering that connected the island to the main island of Honshu via three distinct [expressways](/Expressways_of_Japan). These vital arteries are:

*   The [Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway](/Honsh%C5%AB-Shikoku_Bridge_Project), serving the eastern part of Shikoku.
*   The [Nishiseto Expressway](/Nishiseto_Expressway), providing access to western Shikoku.
*   The [Seto-Chūō Expressway](/Honsh%C5%AB-Shikoku_Bridge_Project), connecting central Shikoku.

The eastern gateway to Shikoku, the city of [Naruto](/Naruto,_Tokushima) in [Tokushima Prefecture](/Tokushima_Prefecture), has been directly linked to the [Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway](/Honsh%C5%AB-Shikoku_Bridge_Project) since its completion in 1998. This particular route establishes a crucial connection between Shikoku and the densely populated [Kansai](/Kansai) area on Honshu, which includes the sprawling [conurbations](/Conurbation) of [Osaka](/Osaka), [Kyoto](/Kyoto), and [Kobe](/Kobe). Consequently, the Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway carries a substantial volume of traffic, facilitating both commercial and passenger transport. Numerous highway bus services operate frequently between the [Kansai](/Kansai) region and [Tokushima Prefecture](/Tokushima_Prefecture), offering convenient inter-island travel.

The central part of Shikoku, prior to the comprehensive bridge network, relied heavily on ferries and air travel for connections to Honshu. However, since 1988, the completion of the [Great Seto Bridge](/Great_Seto_Bridge) network has dramatically transformed accessibility. Before these bridges, the region was, by many accounts, considerably isolated from the economic and social currents of the rest of Japan. The freer movement of goods and people between Honshu and Shikoku was widely anticipated to ignite significant economic development on both sides of these engineering marvels. Unfortunately, the grand promises of such development have not, as yet, fully materialized, leading to ongoing discussions about regional revitalization strategies.

Within Shikoku itself, a comprehensive network of [expressways](/Expressways_of_Japan) and [national highways](/National_highways_of_Japan) efficiently links its major population centers. These include critical routes such as the [Kōchi Expressway](/K%C5%8Dchi_Expressway), [Matsuyama Expressway](/Matsuyama_Expressway), [Takamatsu Expressway](/Takamatsu_Expressway), and [Tokushima Expressway](/Tokushima_Expressway), alongside national routes like [Routes 11](/Japan_National_Route_11), [32](/Japan_National_Route_32), [33](/Japan_National_Route_33), [55](/Japan_National_Route_55), and [56](/Japan_National_Route_56), all designed to facilitate intra-island travel and commerce.

### Rail

The island's rail services are primarily operated by the [Shikoku Railway Company](/Shikoku_Railway_Company) (JR Shikoku), which also provides connections to Honshu via the impressive [Great Seto Bridge](/Great_Seto_Bridge) railway line. JR Shikoku’s network on the island includes:

*   [Dosan Line](/Dosan_Line)
*   [Honshi Bisan Line](/Honshi_Bisan_Line)
*   [Kōtoku Line](/K%C5%8Dtoku_Line)
*   [Mugi Line](/Mugi_Line)
*   [Naruto Line](/Naruto_Line)
*   [Seto Ōhashi Line](/Seto_%C5%8Chashi_Line)
*   [Tokushima Line](/Tokushima_Line)
*   [Uchiko Line](/Uchiko_Line)
*   [Yodo Line](/Yodo_Line)
*   [Yosan Line](/Yosan_Line)

In addition to the JR network, several private railway lines operate within each of Shikoku's four prefectures, serving local communities and supplementing the main inter-prefectural routes. These private lines often offer unique scenic routes and connect to areas less accessible by the broader JR system.

### Air Travel

While Shikoku does not boast a full-fledged international airport, it is adequately served by four regional/domestic airports: [Tokushima Airport](/Tokushima_Airport), [Takamatsu Airport](/Takamatsu_Airport), [Kōchi Ryōma Airport](/Ryoma_Airport), and [Matsuyama Airport](/Matsuyama_Airport). These airports provide essential air links, primarily offering regular flights to Tokyo (Narita and Haneda) and other significant Japanese cities such as [Osaka](/Osaka), [Nagoya](/Nagoya), [Sapporo](/Sapporo), and [Fukuoka](/Fukuoka,_Fukuoka). For international connectivity, [Asiana Airlines](/Asiana_Airlines) operates scheduled flights to [Seoul](/Seoul), [South Korea](/South_Korea), from both [Matsuyama](/Matsuyama,_Ehime) and [Takamatsu](/Takamatsu). Furthermore, periodic international charter flights are arranged, catering to specific seasonal demand or tour groups, further enhancing Shikoku's accessibility to a global audience, albeit on a limited basis.

### Sea Travel

Ferries continue to play a crucial role in Shikoku's transportation network, providing vital links to various destinations. These sea routes connect Shikoku not only to Honshu and [Kyushu](/Kyushu) but also to the numerous smaller islands scattered around Shikoku itself, many of which are otherwise inaccessible. These ferry services are important for both local residents and tourists, offering a scenic and often more economical alternative to land and air travel, and preserving a traditional mode of transport that has shaped the island's connectivity for centuries.

